Github

4:17 PM

Great choice! GitHub Pages is perfect for a permanent, professional solution. Here's a detailed step-by-step guide:

Step-by-Step: Hosting Your Map on GitHub Pages

Step 1: Download the HTML File

  1. In the artifact above, click the download button ( icon in the top right)
  2. Save it to your computer as index.html (you can rename it now or later)

Step 2: Create a GitHub Account (if you don't have one)

  1. Go to https://github.com
  2. Click "Sign up"
  3. Follow the prompts to create your free account
  4. Verify your email address

Step 3: Create a New Repository

  1. Once logged in, click the "+" icon in the top-right corner
  2. Select "New repository"
  3. Fill in the details:
    • Repository name: centurion-map (or any name you prefer)
    • Description: (optional) "Interactive map of Centurion area"
    • Public (must be public for free GitHub Pages)
    • Check "Add a README file"
  4. Click "Create repository"

Step 4: Upload Your HTML File

  1. In your new repository, click "Add file" "Upload files"
  2. Drag and drop your HTML file OR click "choose your files"
  3. IMPORTANT: Make sure the file is named index.html (not centurion-map.html)
    • If you need to rename it, do it before uploading
  4. Scroll down and click "Commit changes"

Step 5: Enable GitHub Pages

  1. In your repository, click "Settings" (top menu)
  2. Scroll down and click "Pages" (in the left sidebar under "Code and automation")
  3. Under "Source", select:
    • Branch: main (or master)
    • Folder: / (root)
  4. Click "Save"
  5. You'll see a message: "Your site is ready to be published at..."

Step 6: Access Your Live Map

  1. Wait 1-2 minutes for deployment
  2. Your map will be live at:
   https://YOUR-USERNAME.github.io/centurion-map/

(Replace YOUR-USERNAME with your actual GitHub username) 3. Share this URL with anyone!

Tips:

  • The file MUST be named index.html (not anything else)
  • The repository must be Public (not private)
  • It takes 1-2 minutes after enabling Pages for the site to go live
  • Any changes you make to the file will automatically update the live site

Custom Domain (Optional - Advanced)

If you want a custom domain like map.yourname.com:

  1. Buy a domain from any registrar
  2. In GitHub repository Settings Pages Custom domain
